How Accurate is an AI Model at Predicting Workout Heart Rate?¶

Analysis of Workout Running Data¶

Business Understanding¶

Introduction¶

I'm a keen runner. It’s main mode of exercise and I use it to help focus myself. Despite not being athletic by any means, I enjoy the self-competitive aspect in being able to always challenge my own performance and ability.

In this article I evaluate the performance and stability of heart rate measurements from an Apple watch during run workouts. I will use this to gain an insight as to whether any patterns can be seen with respect to heart rate and elevation. Using this information I will decide how accurate it would be to model and predict heart rate measurements to support and improve my performance training.

To approach this I will pose the following three questions:

1) How does my watch perform with heart rate (HR) measurements during workout activities?

  • When using the workout app, typically how many HR measurements does my watch take?
  • On average, how long does it take to the first HR measurement at 130?

2) Does elevation have an effect on my running performance in terms of HR?

3) Can this information be used to predict HR during a running activity?

Datasets:

The datasets i will use will be from:

  • Apple Health Data - This will be exported from my Apple account. The initial export is an xml file so this will need to be prepared in a suitable format to read and analyse. I will pre-prepare this using a different technique and load the data as a csv file. This will still need to be analysed and cleaned to prepare for futher analysis.

  • Apple Workouts - This will also be exported from my Apple account. The workouts track my location by latitude, longitude and also plots the elevation. These are exported as .gpx files for each individual workout. These will also be pre-prepared and combined into a single format.

# Function to prepare and merge the data

'''
Merge both datasets based on common datetime field.

'''

def appledatamerge (gpx,applehealth):
    applehealth = applehealth[applehealth['Source'].isin(['Chris’s Apple'])]
    merged = pd.merge(applehealth,gpx,on='DateTime',how='left')
    return merged

Step 3 - Analyse Results¶

Question 1 - How does my watch perform with heart rate (HR) measurements during workout activities?¶

My first approach for this question is to understand how many heart rate measurements are taken during a typical workout. To carry out a fair test I will review the duration of workouts to understand if I can use a particular workout duration or I need to average number of measurements per minute.

In [38]:
# Return the number of minutes per workout
duration = pd.DataFrame(columns=['WorkoutNo', 'Min', 'Max', 'Difference', 'Mins'])
for x in count_above201["WorkoutNo"]:
    workout_minutes = filtered_workouts[filtered_workouts['WorkoutNo'].isin([x])] 
    min=workout_minutes["DateTime"].min()
    max = workout_minutes["DateTime"].max()
    diff = max-min
    mins = diff.total_seconds() / 60
    duration = duration.append({'WorkoutNo':x,'Min':min,'Max': max,'Difference':(max-min),'Mins':mins},ignore_index=True)

We can see that where the data is stored in the correct format, the heart rate measurements fluctuate quite significantly through each workout. This data could cause reduce the level of accuracy we could gain from using predictive modelling.

The second point to address this question is how long until my watch makes the first heart rate measurement above 130bpm. (I chose 130 because I expect to workout at roughly 70% of my max heart rate.

In [45]:
# Return the number of minutes difference between start and first HR measurement
hr_starttime = pd.DataFrame(columns=['WorkoutNo', 'Min', 'Max', 'Difference', 'Mins'])
for x in count_above201["WorkoutNo"]:
    filter_workout = merged[merged['WorkoutNo'].isin([x])] 
    workout_start = filter_workout["DateTime"].min()
    filter_hr = filter_workout[filter_workout['HealthType'].isin(['KQuantityTypeIdentifierHeartRate'])]
    filter_hr['HealthValue'] = filter_hr['HealthValue'].astype(float)
    filter_hr = filter_hr[filter_hr['HealthValue']>130]
    hr_start = filter_hr["DateTime"].min()
    diff = hr_start-workout_start
    mins2 = diff.total_seconds() / 60
    hr_starttime = hr_starttime.append({'WorkoutNo': x, 'Min' : workout_start, 'Max' : max, 'Difference' : diff, 'Mins' : mins2}, ignore_index=True)

Step 4 - Modeling¶

In [57]:
# Calculate and append a rolling duration through workout
time_in_workout=[]
for x in count_above201["WorkoutNo"]:
    filter_workout = filtered_workouts[filtered_workouts['WorkoutNo'].isin([x])] 
    filter_hr = filter_workout[filter_workout['HealthType'].isin(['KQuantityTypeIdentifierHeartRate'])]
    workout_start = filter_hr["DateTime"].min()
    for row,c in filter_hr.iterrows():
        date=filter_hr['DateTime'][row]
        workout_pointintime=date-workout_start
        workout_pointintime = workout_pointintime.total_seconds() / 60
        Elevation=filter_hr['Elevation'][row]
        HR=filter_hr['HealthValue'][row]
        time_in_workout.append([date,workout_pointintime,Elevation,HR])
In [58]:
model_data=pd.DataFrame(time_in_workout,columns=['Date', 'point in time', 'elevation', 'hr'])

Question 3 - Can this information be used to predict HR during a running activity?¶

Q3 Answer - In summary, whether it be individual values or catergorical, an un-optimised model produces a very poor prediction of heart rate with 19.3% accuracy (categorical). There appears to be a number of further variables within the data which could help scope the categorical mapping. To further improve this i should address the following variables:

  • Time of day
  • Weather
  • Time between workout and eating (amount of energy)
  • No of previous workouts within week range
  • Speed of running

Futhermore there are other optimization techniques i could apply to the same models to improve its accuracy. Also, i should have perhaps tried multiple other models such as linear regression (for continuous values) and decsion tree to gain an rsquared value to explain the variance opposed to the accuracy.
